t15. Smith: "A Looming Problem Which Is Going to Have to Be Faced" -- t16. Smith: "Recommitting to Its Original, Pioneering Purpose" -- t17. Wellesley: "Should Wellesley Jump on the Bandwagon?" -- t18. Wellesley: "Having the Courage to Remain a Women's College" -- tPart III. Revisiting the Ivies: Dartmouth -- t19. Dartmouth: "For God's Sake, for Everyone's Sake, Keep the Damned Women Out" -- t20. Dartmouth: "Our Cohogs" -- tPart IV. The United Kingdom: Cambridge and Oxford -- t21. Cambridge: "Like Dropping a Hydrogen Bomb in the Middle of the University" -- t22. Cambridge: "A Tragic Break with Centuries of Tradition" -- t23. Oxford: "Our Crenellations Crumble, We Cannot Keep Them Out" -- t24. Oxford: As Revolutionary as "the Abolition of Celibacy among the Dons" -- tPart V. Taking Stock -- t25. Epilogue -- tManuscript Collections and Oral History Transcripts: Abbreviations -- tInterviews -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the tumultuous decade of the 1960s ended, a number of very traditional, very conservative, highly prestigious colleges and universities in the United States and the United Kingdom decided to go coed, seemingly all at once, in a remarkably brief span of time. Coeducation met with fierce resistance. As one alumnus put it in a letter to his alma mater, "Keep the damned women out." Focusing on the complexities of institutional decision making, this book tells the story of this momentous era in higher education-revealing how coeducation was achieved not by organized efforts of women activists, but through strategic decisions made by powerful men.In America, Ivy League schools like Harvard, Yale, Princeton, and Dartmouth began to admit women; in Britain, several of the men's colleges at Cambridge and Oxford did the same. What prompted such fundamental change? How was coeducation accomplished in the face of such strong opposition? How well was it implemented? Nancy Weiss Malkiel explains that elite institutions embarked on coeducation not as a moral imperative but as a self-interested means of maintaining a first-rate applicant pool. She explores the challenges of planning for the academic and non-academic lives of newly admitted women, and shows how, with the exception of Mary Ingraham Bunting at Radcliffe, every decision maker leading the charge for coeducation was male.Drawing on unprecedented archival research, "Keep the Damned Women Out" is a breathtaking work of scholarship that is certain to be the definitive book on the subject.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aCoeducationzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aCoeducationzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCollege administratorszGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aCollege administratorszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aUniversities and collegeszGreat BritainxAdministrationxHistoryy20th century. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxAdministrationxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxEducation (Higher)zGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomenxEducation (Higher)zUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh  aAmy Gutmann.  aBlack Power.  aDerek Bok.  aEqual Rights Amendment.  aHanna Holborn Gray.  aLawrence Summers.  aNAACP.  aRobert F. Goheen.  aSeven Sisters.  aWilliam G. Bowen.  aantiwar movement.  acultural revolution.  adiscrimination on the basis of sex.  adiversity.  aequal access.  aequal rights.  afeminism.  afeminist.  agender diversity.  agender imbalance.  agender-blind admissions.  aincome discrimination.  aold boy network.  aprotest movements.  asex discrimination.  asex-blind admissions.  asexual discrimination.  asexual harassment.  astudent movements.  asuffrage.  